title: V5 and V6 E3D bowden hotend elevated mount. With 40 mm fan. For Prusa i2.

description.text:
UPDATE: Just posted the new V6 version. It will be tested soon, and pictures will be posted Strongly based on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:154938, but not derived. This mount cools the heatsink of the bowden version of the E3D nozzle V5 with a 40mm fan, and locates it in an elevated position to gain extra height (YAY!!!). This is a wind up toy using all simple parts that can be produced on a 3D printer.  The spring and stop may need some experimenting with, but the mechanics and concept are simple and reliable.
I think the gears and spring mechanisms do a great job of demonstrating the capabilities of 3D printers and the out-of-the-box mentality the MakerBot giveaway is encouraging.

Assembly:
Just print up the parts and assemble in accordance with the part call-out image.  For the axles, use 3/8" D-profile shaft (mcmaster.com part # 8632T2) then use several 3/8" shaft collars (mcmaster part # 6435K13) to hold the shafts and wheels at the correct alignment positions. For the pin that hold the Latch ,Stop and Spring in location use 1/8" dowel pins (mcmaster part #  98381A476).  
To keep the rotating parts turning with relatively low friction, nylon washers can be used to separate the flush surfaces (mcmaster part # 90295A471).  
To keep the Stop and Latch located over the Ratchet, 1/8" ID x 1/4" Long spacers are required (mcmaster part # 94639A332).
Operation:
Make sure the Latch is flipped away from the vehicles body.  Turn the wheels on the left side of the main image, counter clock-wise as shown.  This will wind up the coil spring.  Then flip the inward and let the vehicle take-off!

remixed_from.title: Eric's Improved Z Axis Coupler Rev3

description.text: Few more mods to Eric's awesome coupler idea. Made it hex shape so you can get a shifter (adjustable spanner) onto it - and yes it can take the torque, also added three grub screws at the top. This prints side-ways without the need for supports and came out really well.

Just print it.
3 perimeters, 3 layers, 0.35 nozzle, 0.25mm layer height, 25% infill at 90 degrees fill angle.
Motor end is printed at 5mm so clean it out with a 5mm drill.
Threaded rod end is printed at 9mm so should be a comfortable fit as it comes off the printer.
M8 nut fits inside the open end of the hex coupler.
Run another M8 nut up from below with a washer and tighten it as much as you dare.

comments.text: This worked great! Minus the whole standard nut being too big to fit, nothing a little grinding couldn't fix.

comments.text: Nice to see this design still being popular.  I'm beginning on an i3 for .35/.25mm printing.  I believe these will work, but the i3 uses thinner X threaded rods so I'll be making an adjustment to these.  :-) Keep up the good work.

title: Picture Frame Bracket to fit IKEA Ribba frames

description.text:
We recently bought some Ikea picture frames and were having trouble mounting them on the wall. I came up with this design for two brackets which screw to the back of the deep frame enabling a piece of string, cord or wire to be stretched across between the brackets to facilitate mounting the picture. Simple but effective I think. (A bit like me!!!) this is the picture frame it fits
http://www.ikea.com/gb/en/catalog/products/70153160/ I modified the design after printing out the first two to make it easier to get the screwdriver to put the screws in. This is the second iteration of the design but might still need to be modified.

I designed the part in Solid works 2012 and made it on the UP PLUS 2 supplied by Denford.  It is very similar to things you can buy in brass or plastic to hang pictures, but I've made it to fit these particular picture frames.  
Not my first 3D printed design or product but all the others are very specific to GCSE Engineering projects I am developing with my students so I'm not sure how relevant they would be to the general populous

description.text: This pen holder will keep your writing utensils organized and hold your Samsung S4 in portrait or landscape mode.  Its inspiration is pistons, piston rods, and motor brackets.

4) Position the Connector and Connector Cap around the base of the Cup, and use (2) 3/8" long #6-32 Cap Screws to secure them together. I used Stainless Steel hardware from Home Depot; part number 71038. Hardware datasheet:

title: Ultimaker RTV Silicone anti-vibration feet template

description.text:
Ultimaker RTV Silicone anti-vibration feet template
A Template to form anti-vibration feet / cooling feet.
This is a link to a Video of previous silicone projects, the theory is the same.
http://youtu.be/OaK46BK0zEY To download the latest versions visit my see my Webpages stash
http://intensewalkera.webspace.virginmedia.com/ mix up your silicone and catalyst and pour.
i used rtv 2020 silcone/catalyst. (Medium Hardness)
checkout how to make the rtv silicone mix on google etc, there is plenty of info on there. i used medium hardness silicone as a guess. These feet also allow for about a 25mm increase in height, to allow better airflow for the electronics and better access to the Junk* that accumulates underneath.

i use Cura on my Ultimaker Original to prepare the print.
see the uploaded jpeg for my base settings.
The photos differ slightly to the actual stl files, as i printed a hybrid double version.
i will modify these stl files again shortly, so that it is easier to remove the mold, i will make a "cake tin" style template for someone else to test. The V1 mold is fine, it just required a bit of patience to remove it.
Just keep working the edges away with a wide flat tool and eventually you can work it loose.
